default1.1
default              
defaultThe undertaking of Cycle Proofing / Cycle Audits 
defaultis
default an essential way 
defaultof ensuring
default that 
defaultany
default changes to the highway network are not only safe for cyclists
default but, where possible, positively 
defaultencourage more people to cycle more often. 
defaultThere is already DfT supported guidance on this subject and no more is need, just its application.
default1.2
default              
defaultSuch audits sho
defaultuld not be combined with Safety Audits as their objects are not the same. Safety audits confine themselves only to issues 
defaultof safety 
defaultand are not obliged to identify ways in which 
defaultschemes
default can be improved to achieve the key objectives of Cycle Proofing/Audits
default. An example is highlighted that shows that other countries have made such procedures mandatory and if not followed can put the future of a scheme into jeopardy.
default 
default1.3
default              
defaultThe submission includes a case study which seeks to explain to the committee why the abse
defaultnce of such procedures leads to unsafe schemes. It suggests that the issues highlighted could be avoided through the creation of a properly trained workforce that knows about 
defaultand 
defaultfollows best practice. This situation can be addressed by encouraging authori
defaultties to increase the skill levels of their staff
default through suitable training
default.
default1.4
default              
defaultFinally, the submission sets out an easily adopted principle of how such audit procedures and training could be funded
default from scheme costs without too great a burden on an indivi
defaultdual project thus ensuring value for money. Again, an overseas example of where this is applied is included.
defaultThis submission recommends the following:
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe undertaking of a Cycle Audit should be adopted by the industry as best practice f
defaultor all changes to the highway network (Safety Audits are not compulsory for the local road network but are seen as an essential part of scheme development to ensure user safety);
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe government should inform all local highway authorities that it expects th
defaultis practice to be adopted even if this fall short of compulsion;
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe government should inform local highway authorities that it expects that the costs of Cycle Audits should be met from individual project costs
default;
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe government should inform local highway a
defaultuthorities that they may meet the costs of raising the skills of their staff from scheme costs
default, both capital and revenue,
default where the training demonstrably 
defaultcontributes
default to the delivery of best practice 
defaultth
defaultrougho
defaultut
default those schemes.
