default4.2
default              
defaultIn 2011 a new road was opened close to the centre the county town of 
defaulta shire county
default. This project was funded from government capital funds and developer contribution. During its gestation 
defaultperiod 
defaultobjections were r
defaultaised at the planning approval stage on the basis that elements of the scheme were unsafe for cyclists. 
defaultAt that time it was pointed out that t
defaulthe authority 
defaulthad not chosen best practice by not undertaking a cycle audit. The council rebutted this by claiming 
defaultthat its inclusion in the safety audit was an adequate approach
default. 
defaultThe objections were not taken on board at that time. 
defaultFurther objections were raised at the formal 
defaultland acquisition stage and this resulted an inquiry 
defaultdetermined
default through written representation
defaults.
default Again, the objections were not upheld.
default 
default4
default.3
default              
defaultThe objections presented 
defaultset out
default a number of safety concerns
default. It also pointed out that the needs of cyclists were not considered as part of the schemes development with no mention of their number and desire li
defaultnes in the supporting traffic assessment. This was considered important by the objector since 
defaultthe town’s
default urban wards boasted over 9% journeys to work by bicycle in the 2001 Census. It was also known to impact upon existing cycle routes which linked to such destinations as a secondary school, a further education college and the town’s hospital, all of which a
defaultre recognised as cycling destinations. In the absence of any analysis of their needs, any 
defaultstatement that the scheme in any way met them 
defaultcould not be considered as valid.
